"about 1340–1383","1340–1383":"1340–1383","1348–1389":"1348–1389","1352–Female":"1352–Deceased","1364–1442":"1364–1442","1367–1460":"1367–1460","1369–Female":"1369–Deceased","1309–1363":"1309–1363","1310–1360":"1310–1360","1363":"1363","1352":"1352","abt 1360":"about 1360","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1348":"1348","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1389":"1389","1310":"1310","1442":"1442","1364":"1364","about 1352":"about 1352","1309":"1309","about 1340":"about 1340","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Aldwark, Yorkshire, England":"Aldwark, Yorkshire, England","Alderwarke Castle, Yorkshire, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Penistone, Yorkshire, England":"Penistone, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clarell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Clavel  .","Altered form of French   Clavel  .","Catalan: from <i>clavell</i> ‘clove’, earlier also ‘nail’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for a spice trader or a nail maker."],"variants":[{"name":"Clavel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Alfredo, Angel, Bernardina, Carlos, Consuelo, Fernando, Gustavo, Jeronimo, Jorge, Luis, Margarita.  French Andre, Eugenie, Fernande, Jean-Claude, Pierre.","Spanish: from <i>clavel</i> ‘clove’, earlier also ‘nail’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for a spice trader or a nail maker.","French: from Old French <i>clavel</i> ‘bolt (of a door or gate)’ or ‘nail, link, ring (of chain mail)’, used as a metonymic occupational name for a maker or seller. Compare   Clewell  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Clarell was born about 1340, in Penistone, Yorkshire, England, his father, Thomas Clarell, was 32 and his mother, Isabella Comyn, was 32. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Elizabeth de Reygate. He died in 1383, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 44."},"et":{"about 1340–1383":"umbes 1340–1383","1340–1383":"1340–1383","1348–1389":"1348–1389","1352–Female":"1352–Surnud","1364–1442":"1364–1442","1367–1460":"1367–1460","1369–Female":"1369–Surnud","1309–1363":"1309–1363","1310–1360":"1310–1360","1363":"1363","1352":"1352","abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1348":"1348","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1389":"1389","1310":"1310","1442":"1442","1364":"1364","about 1352":"umbes 1352","1309":"1309","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Aldwark, Yorkshire, England":"Aldwark, Yorkshire, England","Alderwarke Castle, Yorkshire, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Peniston